description: 'So I built a place to say them. On why this site exists and what I hope to do with it.'
---

I'd been going back and forth on having my own space online for a while. Not a LinkedIn profile. Not a PDF resume. Something more... mine.

2025 has been a year of intense professional growth. It's helped me keep learning about technology, teams, product, and‚Äîespecially‚ÄîAI. Somewhere along the way, I realized I had things to say. Thoughts that kept getting stuck in hallway conversations or scattered notes that never went anywhere.

So here we are.

## Why this website

The motivation is simple: I wanted a space where ideas don't just sit in scattered notes. A site that evolves, that reflects not just what I've done, but how I think about things. Private notes collect dust. Writing in public‚Äîor preparing a talk‚Äîforces you to structure, to defend, to improve.

There's also a practical side: having a place where, if someone wants to know how I think professionally, they can get the real picture. Not textbook _personal branding_ with content strategies and editorial calendars. Something more organic.

But above all, I want to **share what I learn**. Over these years I've accumulated thoughts on teams, product, technology, and yeah, mistakes. If any of it helps you dodge a stumble or see a problem from a different angle, then the post was worth writing.

## On the building process

I built this site in a matter of hours. Yes, hours. Not because it's simple (I think it packs quite a visual punch), but because I wanted to push the limits of AI-assisted development.

It's been a fascinating experiment. The iteration speed you get when you use these tools right is insane. Try an idea, throw it out, try another, refine... all in a very tight loop. This is the kind of development that gets me excited: fast, visual, instant feedback.

I wanted the design to be bold. No generic templates. Something with personality, that shows there's someone behind it who actually cares about the details.

## What you'll find here

Honestly, a bit of everything. Thoughts on:

- **Technical leadership and teams**: What I learn day-to-day managing developers.
- **Product**: That mindset I try to keep ‚Äîthat code should serve something beyond passing tests.
- **Technology**: React, architecture, testing, whatever comes up.
- **AI applied to development**: Context Engineering, tools, workflows.
- **Software philosophy**: The uncomfortable questions about how we build software and why.

If you're interested in how to make a technical team work better, or how AI can change the way you develop, you'll probably find something useful here.

I don't have a publishing schedule. I'm not going to promise you a post every week. I'll publish when I have something worth saying. Hopefully this won't be the first and last, but I'm not going to force content just to fill space either.

---

If you've made it this far, thanks for stopping by. This is just getting started.
